<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="99" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
57. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138766" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera aliena Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aliena">Ponera aliena</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="99" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
Worker. Length 1 1/2 line.-Scarcely differing from the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:179253" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera contracta (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="contracta">Ponera contracta</taxonomicName>
of Europe; the antennae are however rather shorter, and the apical joint longer; the legs are shorter and thicker; but the most distinctive difference is the thickness of the scale, or node of the petiole, which in the present species is much thicker, particularly at its upper margin; in other respects they scarcely differ: the eyes are wanting, as in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:179253" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera contracta (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="contracta">P. contracta</taxonomicName>
: the palpi have not been examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="99" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="99">Hab. Brazil. (Coll.W. Swainson.)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="99" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="99">
This species doubtless resembles very closely the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138043" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera ruficornis Spinola" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruficornis">Ponera ruficornis</taxonomicName>
of Spinola, but he describes his insect as black, with red antennae: our species is entirely of a brownish-yellow, and appears to he distinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
